 immune responses. Clinical stages of rabies can progress from incubation period (5 days to >2 years: U.S. median ~35 days) to prodrome state (0-10 days) to acute neurologic period (2-7 days) to coma (5-14 days) to death. Once in tissues at the entry site, rabies virus can be neutralized by passively administered rabies immune globulin (RIG). Active immunization (vaccine) stimulates the host immune system, and, as a result, virus-neutralizing antibodies (VNA) are produced approximately 7-10 days after initiation of vaccination. By approximately day 14-28 (after administration of 4 vaccine doses), VNAs peak. In the absence of early and adequate PEP, virus enters host neurons, spreads to the central nervous system, and causes disease, with inevitably fatal consequence.","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":582,"renderedHeight":358,"naturalWidth":582,"naturalHeight":358,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 899 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":22275},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/figures/r5902a1f2.gif","alt":"Figure 2 depicts the number of cases of documented rabies PEP failures in Burma, India, the Philippines, South Africa, Sri Lanka, and Thailand during 1984-2007. Of 21 reported PEP failures described, 20 patients had symptoms and 15 died before day 28. The majority of cases of symptom onset and death occurred during days 14-28.","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":517,"renderedHeight":251,"naturalWidth":517,"naturalHeight":251,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 328 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":5473},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/TemplatePackage/images/icon_out.png","alt":"External Web Site Icon","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaH